# Rich Library Projects Documentation  

## 📊 System Monitoring Dashboard  
I built a live console dashboard that displays CPU, memory, and task progress in real time. 
The reason I built this was to monitor system performance interactively and avoid cluttered logs, 
while showcasing Rich’s ability to create dynamic layouts. At a high level, the console is divided into sections using 
Rich’s `Layout`. Progress bars and status indicators are updated continuously with `Live` and `Progress`, 
and metrics are refreshed at intervals to give the appearance of a real-time monitoring tool. Through this project, 
I learned that Rich can transform the terminal into a dynamic monitoring interface, making it useful for system administration 
and pipelines beyond simple text output.  

---

## ✅ Task Tracker  
I built a CLI-based task tracker that organizes tasks in a table and shows their progress with spinners or progress bars. 
I chose to build this to demonstrate how Rich can be used to manage and visualize tasks in a structured, 
colorful way, similar to a lightweight project board. The tracker works by displaying tasks in a Rich `Table`, 
where each row represents a task. Rich’s `Status` or `Progress` components update the task’s state until completion. 
From this project, I learned that Rich tables can act like a mini project management board inside the console, 
making task tracking more intuitive and visually appealing.  

---

## 🌐 Flask Integration  
I built a lightweight web dashboard that serves Rich tables as HTML via Flask. 
The motivation for building this was to explore how Rich can extend beyond the console and 
integrate with web applications, providing styled output in a browser. The way it works is that Rich renderables 
(like tables) are printed to a `Console(record=True)` and then exported as HTML. 
Flask serves that HTML through a route, allowing Rich’s styled components to appear in a web dashboard. 
From this project, I learned that Rich isn’t limited to terminals — it can generate styled HTML for dashboards, 
making it useful in web contexts and developer-facing tools.  

